25|$|Clarke was {{a lifelong}} proponent of space travel. In 1934, while still a teenager, {{he joined the}} British Interplanetary Society. In 1945, he {{proposed}} a <b>satellite</b> <b>communication</b> system, an idea which won him the Franklin Institute's Stuart Ballantine Medal in 1963, and other honours. Later he {{was the chairman of}} the British Interplanetary Society from 1946–47 and again in 1951–53.|$|E
25|$|ACARS {{can send}} {{messages}} over VHF if a VHF ground station network {{exists in the}} current area of the aircraft. VHF communication is line-of-sight propagation and the typical range is up to 200 nautical miles at high altitudes. Where VHF is absent, an HF network or <b>satellite</b> <b>communication</b> may be used if available. Satellite coverage may be limited at high latitudes (trans-polar flights).|$|E
